WhiteboardMng is a static buddy allocator over u64-aligned wh8 slabs sized to the map (w*h*8 bytes each). init(w, h, slab_lim) sets the slab cap (default 100, max 100); each slab tracks eight wh1 sub-slots in one byte of the slot bitmap. Checkout picks the fullest slab that still fits a 1/2/4/8-byte-per-tile request, or lazy-allocates until slab_lim is reached; on exhaustion co() returns a null ptr and RAII wrappers set ok() false without aborting. Protected checkout returns a byte pointer plus (blk, sub); release clears bits and coalesces implicitly. Callers confirm success via wrapper ok() and defer work when false. WhiteboardMngTestUtil drives scripted sequences, return policies, slab_lim, and traces under wb_vtest_trace/.

What is still missing: adv_map_gen has not migrated off the old fixed-u16 Whiteboard; sub-chunk pointers are not generally u64-aligned; rd_i/wr_i skip bounds checks unless WB_TRACE_DB is enabled; there is no chkout or pressure API for early deferral; and no automated trace analyzer yet. Integration wrappers for common patterns (e.g. a 2B distance field matching today's u16 sheet) are also not written.

Checkout failure handling: programmer errors (zero dims, double init, checkout before init) still abort. Runtime exhaustion (slab cap, malloc failure, no fit in existing slabs) returns null from co(); Whiteboard_1B … 8B set ok() false and skip release on destruction. Hot-path callers such as long-distance reusable pathing should test ok() and skip the job for this turn, retrying later when slabs free up. Map-gen pipelines may use a large slab_lim and still abort on init misuse; runtime code should use a modest cap and the soft path. Optional future: chkout() or fill metrics to defer before attempting checkout.
